pasted-image.tiff
Anything produced can be interpreted both objectively — what is the thing itself? — and subjectively — what was the intention of the maker in expressing that thing?
An objective interpretation, by contrast, only focuses on the product.
Only the interpreter’s meaning-context (subjective) matters here.

Schütz is careful to insist that he’s not talking about empathy here, because we cannot truly place ourselves in the other person’s shoes; we can only interpret their experience using our own raw material.
